<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900904-0105</DOCNO><DOCID>900904-0105.</DOCID><HL>   Marketing andamp; Media:   Men and Smart Magazines   To Become Smart: for Men</HL><DATE>09/04/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B9</SO><CO>   WNEWS</CO><IN>MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)</IN><LP>   NEW YORK -- Scratch one men's magazine.   Men, a magazine that was supposed to launch in early 1991,will instead merge with Smart, a men's magazine published byNew American Magazine Co. Smart, which is 18 months old, willcarry a new, extended title -- Smart: for Men.</LP><TEXT>   Peter Kaplan, the editor who had helped develop Men forFairfield, Conn.-based Norris Publishing, will be the neweditor in chief of Smart. The men's general-interest magazinerecently lost its founding editor Terry McDonell when he wasnamed editor of Hearst Corp.'s Esquire.   Owen Lipstein, chairman of New American Magazine Co., saidChristopher Kimball, one of the founders of NorrisPublishing, will become publishing director of New AmericanMagazine Co. Besides Smart, Mr. Lipstein's New York-basedcompany also publishes Mother Earth News and PsychologyToday.   Mr. Lipstein wouldn't say what he paid to acquire Men; hedid say that many of Mr. Kaplan's ideas for his magazinewould be incorporated into Smart.</TEXT></DOC>